{"attack":true,"case":"The proposal's central mechanism invokes features that are neither defined in measurable quantities nor measurable by rerunning this repository's validation harness. Specifically, the mechanism claims bare 4-of-7 wrong majorities carry 'distinctive candidate-set features (near-tie entropy, higher variance in reasoning quality among the 4)' that a critic can learn to flag. 'Higher variance in reasoning quality among the 4' is not a pre-registered, harness-measurable quantity — the validation harness scores candidate answers against a held-out answer key; it does not compute per-candidate 'reasoning quality' variance within a wrong majority cluster. This violates std-crit-design clause (1), which requires the mechanism to be 'stated in measurable quantities (candidate base error rate, critic precision and recall, ensemble size k)' — not unmeasurable qualitative features. The proposal lists critic precision and recall in its scope, but the explanatory mechanism itself rests on 'near-tie entropy' and 'variance in reasoning quality' that have no operational definition in the repository. Furthermore, the third forbidden case ('the improvement at k=7 is fully explained by base-error change alone with no interaction effect from critic precision on bare-majority sets') requires an interaction-effect decomposition whose statistical power is unspecified and arguably unattainable: with only 100 questions at base error ~0.60, the subset falling in the 0.55-0.65 bin with bare 4-of-7 wrong majorities and critic precision >= 0.7 may be vanishingly small (a handful of questions), making any 'no interaction effect' refutation claim unfalsifiable in practice — violating std-crit-design's requirement that forbidden cases be 'concrete, measurable outcomes of running the proposed experiment.'","counterexample":null}